---
import { Picture } from "astro:assets"
import CaseStudy from "@/layouts/case-study.astro"
import CaseStudySnapshot from "@/components/CaseStudySnapshot.astro"
import { Badge } from "@/components/ui/badge"
import { getProject } from "@/data/projects"
import verdictSfImg from "@/assets/projects/wheely-weather/verdict-sf.png"
import verdictRaleighImg from "@/assets/projects/wheely-weather/verdict-raleigh.png"
import theNumbersImg from "@/assets/projects/wheely-weather/the-numbers.png"
import hourByHourImg from "@/assets/projects/wheely-weather/hour-by-hour.png"
import weekAheadImg from "@/assets/projects/wheely-weather/week-ahead.png"

const project = getProject("wheely-weather")!

const pictureFormats: ("avif" | "webp")[] = ["avif", "webp"]
const pictureWidths = [340, 680, 1020]
const pictureSizes = "(min-width: 640px) 340px, 88vw"
const pairSizes = "(min-width: 640px) 320px, 88vw"

const numbersAnnotations = [
  { label: "Raw signals stay visible", position: "numbers-1" },
  { label: "Scored on the weakest signal", position: "numbers-2" },
]

const hourlyAnnotations = [
  {
    label: "The dip shows the window closing",
    position: "hourly-1",
  },
]

const weekAheadAnnotations = [
  { label: "Best ride day, starred", position: "week-1" },
]

const snapshotItems = [
  {
    label: "Question",
    value: "Is it worth riding right now?",
  },
  {
    label: "Audience",
    value: "Recreational and commuter cyclists planning short-term rides.",
  },
  {
    label: "Core decision",
    value: "Score the weakest weather signal instead of averaging risk away.",
  },
  {
    label: "Built as",
    value:
      "Independent iOS learning project in Swift and SwiftUI, with a watchOS companion in progress. Earlier version shipped as a web app.",
  },
]
---

<CaseStudy
  project={project}
  title="Wheely Weather"
  description="An independent iOS cycling weather project that puts dew point, feels-like temperature, and wind next to a clear ride recommendation."
  seoTitle="Wheely Weather · Independent iOS Cycling Weather Project"
  seoDescription="Wheely Weather is an independent iOS cycling weather project with ride-quality verdicts, hourly riding windows, and weather-based kit guidance."
>
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    Wheely Weather answers one near-term riding question: <em
      >is it worth going now?</em
    > General forecasts show plenty of numbers, but not always the ones that help
    with that call. In conversations with riders, dew point, feels-like temperature,
    and wind came up most often.
  </p>
  <p>
    I am using it as an independent iOS build: verdict first, evidence close,
    and a next ride window when the answer is no. An earlier web version helped
    me test the model before the SwiftUI rewrite.
  </p>

  <CaseStudySnapshot items={snapshotItems} />

  <h2>The Decision Moment</h2>
  <p>
    Before a ride, I was checking one weather app and falling back to another
    when the first came up short. The data was available, but the call was not.
    Six conversations with recreational and commuter cyclists narrowed the
    signals to dew point, feels-like temperature, and wind. Dew point was the
    easiest to miss in the apps people already used. That gap set the direction:
    put the useful signals next to the verdict, and score by the weakest signal
    instead of averaging conditions away.
  </p>
  <p>
    That kept the scope tight. The app had to work at a glance on a phone, state
    the recommendation clearly, and still show enough evidence for riders who
    wanted to check the call.
  </p>

  <h2>Product Direction</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Lead with a five-level ride rating: Great, Good, Fair, Poor, or Bad.
    </li>
    <li>
      Score the weakest riding signal instead of averaging bad conditions away.
    </li>
    <li>Name the limiting condition when the ride rating drops.</li>
    <li>
      Keep the raw weather signals visible for riders who disagree with the
      recommendation.
    </li>
    <li>
      Point to the next usable window before asking anyone to study a chart.
    </li>
    <li>
      Guide kit selection from the same data, so no separate clothing app is
      needed.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <figure class="verdict-pair">
    <div class="verdict-pair__grid">
      <div class="phone phone--cropped">
        <Picture
          src={verdictSfImg}
          formats={pictureFormats}
          widths={[320, 640, 960]}
          sizes={pairSizes}
          alt="Wheely Weather verdict for Seattle on a deep green ride-day card."
        />
      </div>
      <div class="phone phone--cropped">
        <Picture
          src={verdictRaleighImg}
          formats={pictureFormats}
          widths={[320, 640, 960]}
          sizes={pairSizes}
          alt="Wheely Weather verdict for Raleigh on an orange rest-day card calling out heavy humidity."
        />
      </div>
    </div>
    <figcaption>
      The verdict adapts to conditions, green when it’s worth going and orange
      when it isn’t, and names the limiting factor when the answer is no.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2 id="system-design">System Design</h2>
  <p>
    The screen order follows the rider’s question sequence instead of the shape
    of a forecast API: can I go, why did it get that rating, what should I wear?
    The verdict card uses color and a plain-language label rather than a numeric
    score: a number would push the threshold decision back onto the rider, which
    is exactly what the app is trying to resolve. The Numbers panel keeps the
    raw signals close to the verdict, so the recommendation stays explainable.
  </p>

  <figure class="annotated-figure">
    <div class="annotated-figure__media">
      <div class="phone">
        <Picture
          src={theNumbersImg}
          formats={pictureFormats}
          widths={pictureWidths}
          sizes={pictureSizes}
          alt="The Numbers panel showing rain chance, feels-like temperature, wind, air quality, dewpoint, UV index, sunrise, and sunset on individual cards."
        />
      </div>
      <ul class="annotation-list" aria-label="The Numbers annotations">
        {
          numbersAnnotations.map((a) => (
            <li
              class:list={[
                "annotation-list__item",
                `annotation-list__item--${a.position}`,
              ]}
            >
              <Badge variant="outline" className="annotation-badge">
                {a.label}
              </Badge>
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
    </div>
    <figcaption>
      Each signal gets its own card, and the one dragging the rating down is
      flagged inline.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>Riding Windows</h2>
  <p>
    A bad current rating shouldn’t end the session. Hour by Hour turns a “not
    now” into a specific window, while the Week Ahead surfaces the best day to
    ride when today isn’t promising.
  </p>

  <figure class="annotated-figure">
    <div class="annotated-figure__media">
      <div class="phone">
        <Picture
          src={hourByHourImg}
          formats={pictureFormats}
          widths={pictureWidths}
          sizes={pictureSizes}
          alt="Hour-by-Hour panel with a ride-quality chart, a Now marker on the current hour, and Today’s Kit below."
        />
      </div>
      <ul class="annotation-list" aria-label="Hour by Hour annotations">
        {
          hourlyAnnotations.map((a) => (
            <li
              class:list={[
                "annotation-list__item",
                `annotation-list__item--${a.position}`,
              ]}
            >
              <Badge variant="outline" className="annotation-badge">
                {a.label}
              </Badge>
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
    </div>
    <figcaption>
      The chart reads as a window, not a forecast: ride quality by hour, a Now
      marker, and kit guidance below.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <figure class="annotated-figure">
    <div class="annotated-figure__media">
      <div class="phone">
        <Picture
          src={weekAheadImg}
          formats={pictureFormats}
          widths={pictureWidths}
          sizes={pictureSizes}
          alt="The Week Ahead panel showing eight days of ride ratings with the best riding days highlighted."
        />
      </div>
      <ul class="annotation-list" aria-label="Week Ahead annotations">
        {
          weekAheadAnnotations.map((a) => (
            <li
              class:list={[
                "annotation-list__item",
                `annotation-list__item--${a.position}`,
              ]}
            >
              <Badge variant="outline" className="annotation-badge">
                {a.label}
              </Badge>
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
    </div>
    <figcaption>
      When today is off the table, the Week Ahead points to the day worth
      watching.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>Rebuilding for iOS</h2>
  <p>
    The idea started on the web, but the daily use case belongs on a phone.
    Moving to native iOS gave me on-device location, a faster pre-ride glance,
    and a watchOS companion over WatchConnectivity.
  </p>
  <p>
    The information architecture carried over: verdict first, weakest-signal
    scoring, raw evidence close to the recommendation, and riding windows when
    the answer is no. Forecast data comes from Open-Meteo and the National
    Weather Service, with air-quality and alert signals where they affect the
    ride verdict.
  </p>
  <p>
    Implementation splits across shared forecast logic, design tokens, and
    SwiftUI views for the dashboard, location gate, and riding-window panels.
    Mock scenarios help test the UI before live weather data is wired in.
  </p>
  <p>
    AI-assisted coding tools (Cursor, Claude Code, Codex, and OpenCode) helped
    me move faster from product sketches to working UI.
  </p>
  <p>
    The earlier web app on Astro and React (still live at <a
      href="https://wheelyweather.app"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noreferrer">wheelyweather.app</a
    >) tested the verdict-first approach on Cloudflare Pages before the native
    rewrite.
  </p>

  <h2>Outcome</h2>
  <p>
    Wheely Weather is still in development. I use the web app and early native
    builds before rides now, which is enough proof to keep building.
  </p>
  <p>
    The useful pattern was restraint: score the weakest signal, lead with a
    verdict, and keep the rest of the forecast in supporting roles.
  </p>
</CaseStudy>

<style>
  /* Phone-shaped display wrapper around portrait screenshots. */
  .phone {
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 20rem;
    margin: 0 auto;
    aspect-ratio: 9 / 19.5;
    overflow: hidden;
    border-radius: 1.125rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    background: var(--background);
  }

  .phone :global(picture),
  .phone :global(img) {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: top;
  }

  /* Cropped variant for the verdict pair: focuses on the verdict card. The
     two screenshots differ in height, so a fade keeps either crop from
     slicing through content. */
  .phone--cropped {
    aspect-ratio: 4 / 4.6;
    max-width: 22rem;
  }

  .phone--cropped :global(img) {
    mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, black 82%, transparent 100%);
  }

  .verdict-pair__grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: 1rem;
    justify-items: center;
  }

  @media (min-width: 640px) {
    .verdict-pair__grid {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
      gap: 1rem;
    }
  }

  /* Annotated figure: image + side annotations on desktop. */
  .annotated-figure__media {
    position: relative;
  }

  /* Annotations need their connector lines to mean anything; below md the
     figcaption carries the information instead. */
  .annotation-list {
    display: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    list-style: none;
  }

  .annotation-badge {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    min-height: 1.75rem;
    justify-content: flex-start;
    border-color: var(--border);
    background: color-mix(in oklch, var(--background) 92%, transparent);
    padding: 0.3125rem 0.625rem;
    text-align: left;
    white-space: normal;
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    line-height: 1.25;
    color: var(--foreground);
    backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
  }

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    .annotated-figure__media {
      /* Carve out side gutters by constraining the inner phone column. */
    }

    .annotation-list {
      position: absolute;
      inset: 0;
      display: block;
      margin: 0;
      pointer-events: none;
    }

    /* Fixed width (not max-width) so the connector dot, offset by 100% of the
       item, lands at a position independent of how long the label text is. The
       content column is a fixed 45rem at this breakpoint with the 20rem phone
       centered, so --reach alone determines where each dot sits on the image. */
    .annotation-list__item {
      position: absolute;
      width: 12rem;
      --reach: 2.25rem;
    }

    .annotation-list__item::before {
      position: absolute;
      top: 50%;
      width: var(--reach);
      height: 1px;
      background: color-mix(in oklch, var(--foreground) 35%, transparent);
      content: "";
    }

    .annotation-list__item::after {
      position: absolute;
      top: calc(50% - 0.1875rem);
      width: 0.375rem;
      height: 0.375rem;
      border-radius: 999px;
      background: var(--foreground);
      content: "";
    }

    /* The Numbers panel: annotations alternate sides. "Raw signals stay
       visible" gestures at the grid from the right; "Scored on the weakest
       signal" reaches from the left to the POOR flag on the Dewpoint card. */
    .annotation-list__item--numbers-1 {
      top: 14%;
      right: 0;
      --reach: 3.5rem;
    }

    .annotation-list__item--numbers-2 {
      top: 42%;
      left: 0;
      --reach: 6.5rem;
    }

    /* Hour by Hour: single annotation pointing at the descending curve. */
    .annotation-list__item--hourly-1 {
      top: 19%;
      right: 0;
      --reach: 4.5rem;
    }

    /* Week Ahead: annotation pointing at the highlighted best ride day. */
    .annotation-list__item--week-1 {
      top: 30%;
      left: 0;
      --reach: 3rem;
    }

    /* Left-side annotations: connector extends to the right. */
    .annotation-list__item--numbers-2::before,
    .annotation-list__item--week-1::before {
      left: 100%;
    }

    .annotation-list__item--numbers-2::after,
    .annotation-list__item--week-1::after {
      left: calc(100% + var(--reach));
    }

    /* Right-side annotations: connector extends to the left. */
    .annotation-list__item--numbers-1::before,
    .annotation-list__item--hourly-1::before {
      right: 100%;
    }

    .annotation-list__item--numbers-1::after,
    .annotation-list__item--hourly-1::after {
      right: calc(100% + var(--reach));
    }
  }
</style>
